  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Deborah Weston begins the letter by talking about herself. She tells about a fire in Nathaniel T. Bent&apos;s house. She saw a man named Hallett at the Mansion House. She collected signatures for a petition. She praises Rev. Angier and Rev. Choules. Deborah writes: Dr. Wilson &amp; Phineas Crandall, both the Methodist ministers in town, are abolitionists...&quot; She says that Philemon R. Russell spoke. Deborah includes many messages to members of her family.</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Also with Call No. Ms.A.9.2 v.8, p.62, is a receipt from the Anti-Slavery Society, for $20, dated Boston, Oct. 21, 1836.</subfield>
